Well, it seems the Flutter plugin is already using it, too:

https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/blob/906e6db8bb8a50aa99c672a5a1b77137b6f2424e/src/io/flutter/vmService/DartVmServiceDebugProcess.java#L296

@DanTup Do you know if it works correctly in VS Code? I wonder if `suspendContext` is null for some reason.

I am using IntelliJ. The options I have are:

```
F8 - Step Over 
F7 - Step Into 
Alt-Shift-F7 - Force step Into
Shif-F8 - Step Out
Alt-F9 - Run to cursor
```

**None of this options work.** Code I am using is:

```
void main() async {
  print("INI");
  int x = await getValue();
  print('x = $x');
  print("END");
}

Future<int> getValue() async {
  await Future.delayed(Duration(seconds: 1));
  return 42;
}
```

When I am in the line that says `int x = await getValue();` I want to press some key that will send me straight to the `print('x = $x');` line. When I press **F8** It is actually going to the `Future<int> getValue() async {`.

The problem seems to be that the VM is not sending `atAsyncSuspension` in the event as often as we expect it to.

Here's a sample Dart program:
```dart
void main(List<String> arguments) {
  simple();
}

Future<void> simple() async {
  print('main start');
  await
    foo();
  print('main end');
}

Future<void> foo() async {
  print('foo start');
  await Future.delayed(const Duration(microseconds: 100));
  print('foo end');
}
```
I'm using Dart v2.12.4, same as @DanTup, in a Dart project (not a Flutter project). I get odd results, though. Note the newline before the call to `foo()`. If it is there then everything works as expected when I put a breakpoint on the line that calls `foo()`. If I delete the newline before `foo()` (and move the breakpoint to the variable declaration) then the debugger steps into `foo` even when I tell it to step over. So, the newline is significant to something.

When I try this with Flutter, the results are even odder. I generated a sample Flutter project, added the two async functions, and added a call to `simple()` in the call to `setState()`, just before `_counter++;`. If I run it as formatted above I get the same results as with the Dart project. If I remove the newline before `foo()` it gets crazy. Step-over causes it to exit `simple()` and be ready to increment the counter. The next step-over does increment it.

@DanTup could you try this code in a Flutter project, just to confirm this is not a VM problem? The events I'm getting don't have `atAsyncSuspension` set unless the newline is present, or if I've already done step-over once (which is why it exits `simple()`, I believe).
